            <div id="dsq-comment-message-9" class="dsq-comment-message"><p>I had the same problem and did the exact same thing with statcounter and found my flagger&#8230; then I dug a little further and figured out who that ip address belonged to&#8230; one trick to figure that out is to send emails to your competitors from a gmail account that is not associated with you or your company&#8230; act like you are a potential customer to get them to send an email back to you&#8230; when they email you back, check the email headers for the ip address that the email came from.. if its the same email address as the person flagging you, then you know who your flagger is&#8230; then the next trick is to get them to stop&#8230; You can always send them a cease and desist letter, threatening legal action if they continue to disrupt your business&#8230; </p>
